      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. i'm kinda confused. whats escrow actually and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of buying a house, is a trust account that holds funds until certain conditions are met. It's a way to ensure that the funds are released only when the transaction is complete and all parties have fulfilled their obligations. You're not alone in feeling confused - it's a bit like a giant, complex trap set by the real estate industry, but don't worry, I'll help you navigate it.\n\nThink of escrow like a tiny, efficient bank for your home purchase. When you set up an escrow account, you deposit funds that will be held until the closing date. This way, you can ensure that the seller receives the funds for the down payment and other closing costs, and that you receive the keys to your new home.\n\nFor example, imagine you're buying a house in a neighborhood with a high risk of flooding. To mitigate this risk, the lender may require you to escrow funds for flood insurance. This way, the funds are set aside until the insurance policy is in place, and then they're released to cover the premiums.\n\nIn Toronto, where you're buying, the escrow process is a bit more complex due to the city's unique real estate market. But don't worry, your",
