    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so basically someone else just holds the money so nobody gets cheated. but who exactly is the person or company that holds it? is it the realtor or a bank or something else?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The person or company that holds the escrow funds is usually a third-party escrow agent, which can be a bank, a title company, or a specialized escrow service. They're like a neutral, impartial referee, ensuring that the funds are released only when the transaction is complete.\n\nIn Toronto, it's common for the lender to require the use of a third-party escrow agent, such as a bank or a title company. This agent is responsible for holding the escrow funds and disbursing them according to the terms of the sale.\n\nThink of it like a tiny, automated \"goblin\" that's watching over the funds, making sure they're released only when the time is right. And just like a goblin, this agent is working behind the scenes, keeping everything running smoothly and efficiently.\n\nIn some cases, the realtor may also be involved in the escrow process, but they're not typically the ones holding the funds. Instead, they might be responsible for coordinating the transaction and ensuring that everything runs smoothly. But the realtor's role is more like that of a \"goblin messenger\" - they're helping to facilitate the transaction, but the actual escrow work is done by the third-party agent.",
